A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
The leaders of Republicans justify their policies with the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, confirming that the election fraud in the US is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning.
By the way, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for conducting the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that make it difficult to register or pass urns.
This phenomenon has gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives could be recorded in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo identification and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, the right to register as voters on the election day, and the right of citizens to vote for which a court act exists.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required the voters to show a photo identification.
Indiana was the first state to claim such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the law of Indiana in 2008.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, in 34 states, they have promoted draft laws to force voters to show a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, the US citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of US citizens, 21 million eligible persons, do not have a photo identification issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID card.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the necessary ID card.
Young people, minorities and low-income people are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years do not have the necessary photo identification.
This is enough.
Students who are considered to be voters who increasingly vote for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo identification issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same States allow members of fishing or hunting associations to choose more strongly for the Republican side to use the maps issued by those associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to be elected.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting hypanic votes.
For it is obvious that two of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators in 2011 promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general elections have contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
Because the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of registration of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they were only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, which represented 76% of the voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their followers have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the Vetos of democratic governors.
The U.S. Advocate General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote difficult.
The democratic critics condemn the party-political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear objective the influence of the results in the countries that are determining the outcome for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those States that have passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required by the Electoral Board to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes in the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
Prostate cancer early detection: should the test be done or not?
In fact, the PSA test has sometimes shown faulty results, with false negative or false positive results that lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This leads to greater hesitation of the men who have already decided to carry out early detection tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We have obtained the opinion of two specialists.
The studies carried out in the USA have had a number of disturbances between the control groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study has also shown that in follow-up to 12 years, the probability of metastasis formation is 30% to 40% higher if no early detection has been performed.
That is why I recommend the test from the age of 50 or 40 years, if you have a direct relative who was already suffering from prostate cancer.
There is also a higher risk for men of African-American origin.
The most important thing is to make the right decision once cancer has been detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient needs to understand the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options in which prostate cancers can remain untreated if he does not affect the quality of life in the long term, and in these cases he chooses to actively monitor the disease.
Today, there is no treatment for many men who have been diagnosed with cancer, since their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
They are proposed to be actively monitored and offered treatment as the disease progresses.
It is increasingly accurate to determine the criteria for deciding who should be treated and who should not.
That's why I still recommend carrying out the test.
The most important thing, however, is to talk to his doctor to determine whether he should be performed or not.
In cooperation with the international society for urology, Movember has developed an instrument to assess the advantages and disadvantages of the PSA test.
