Higgs boson analyzed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has aroused some attention last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or " least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a large physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure about it.
Still, let's assume that it's actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let's look at what's going on.
There is an indispensable law in this world that makes two objects cannot be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too hard, as you are getting hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to them: the Pauli exclusion principle, which means that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", where this "state" consists largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione, who obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil band of anarchists who are not sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure, these bosons are divided into two groups by the Berkeley laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all so exotic creatures as one could think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a bosons of exceptional banality: the photon or the "light particle" which is the "bote" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at this point, about like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "interference" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of power".
More Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this boson shows up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must achieve very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be crushed by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is necessary - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, they are not all particles and not all materials interacting with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never automatically keep to the refrigerator.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
What can all these research be "good" for now, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to examine in detail all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are by the way numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes of the model.
One has to say that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it does not explain the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found in the CERN.
Impact
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is no such thing.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was initially regarded as rather a "laboratory".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instruments surrounding research.
Willard Boyle, for example, developed a small light sensor during his works in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and brought him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you can never really know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...  Roger Le Devoir
Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life with its "Death in Dignity" committee.
The debate must be resumed soon, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that devoured him had left him a two-year period.
"They gave me five years to live, I made seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the house for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: an immense weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped with food.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to cure my diarrhoea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our life, we learn that a man is pinking in the face," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' home.
To return to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"This depends on the person's ability to take a step back, he notes.
In the view of several people who work in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these steps.
The patients who are sent to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, doctors and nurses who take care of them will no longer be overcrowded with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But because of the illness, I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in life," she says before she accepts that she is put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the next few days, she is still expecting a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
In the home Victor-Gadbois is offered with a group of volunteers personal care and assistance in food intake.
The palliative care is used when there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care on 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little when you take into account that one day we'll all die.
Here, life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on the desire of the deceased, one grants a mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family members and patients alike," reports Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At home Victor-Gadbois is not a day like the other one.
In addition to an old man of 93 years who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while one finds himself in honor, a young man of 36 years who is surrounded by his parents, his wife, and his two little children dies in a tragic way after he has tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel says alarmedly.
53% of patients sent to the home of Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% coming from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that should relieve the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the end stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the home palliative care company in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this major inadequacy in the health care of Quebec that makes sure that several doctors specialising in palliative care look forward to the adoption of a law on the regulation of death and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliatives such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not efficient enough to ensure that all rights to high quality palliative care are maintained before you accept to go to death.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain, without taking measures to ease her.
I fear that patients will only die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of worst predictions by the last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were minimal when she broke down a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she replied to me that she was sorry I gave up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the nurses for not accepting this wish after their pain has been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care in pain treatment is not omnipotent.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care of the community of home palliative care in Greater Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the end of life, the doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which is intended to sleep in the patient either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can't do it any longer than we can't see this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that does not necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep", but "I want my pain to be eased."
