Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "like the conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits" that are used to move forward in a video game that can be won or bought through games (and sometimes exchanged back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, each time trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin all network nodes are at the same time keepers of the invoice book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A series of the related data is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoins are available in the public-accounts invoice book distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, privileged to add this additional line.
This is a piece of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing gets "cracked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
When this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay twice as fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money for fraud, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unconnected, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer who solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divided into a hundred billionths, leaving a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in the computing power.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide Bitcoin services have been attacked and the Bitcoin deposits have been stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who just introduced Paymium, which is a company for payment with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB shall also report on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia deny donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the invoice book and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega-closed sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the Coinabul company, who converts bitcoins to gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses bitcoin to validate the transactions that are therefore cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages its identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter does not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat states that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are considered in favour of more horizontal-oriented systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
By the way, the ECB's report foresees re-evaluating the various risks that are considered highly regarded today in the event of the success of this currency.
