A Constitution with the Brechstenge in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever with regard to the declaration of constitution which temporarily grants it unlimited authority, it has decided to place everything on a map.
To surprise everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constitutional Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this assembly two additional months for the completion of its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been based on a provisional text, which has changed several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal confusion.
This new initiative has only made the country even more divided.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step the right with feet".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining his public and democratic legitimacy while protesting throughout the country rages.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Muhammad Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially the Egyptian people with this recourse to an hasty vote is put an ultimatum: "Either you vote for my draft or I reserve the unlimited authority", the latter should, after the adoption of the Constitution, put an end to it.
85 mostly Islamic members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they have turned their backs on the idea that they have not been able to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
To achieve the decision-making capacity, 11 persons, alternate members, were added in all speeds yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslims.
It is not surprising that the articles were generally adopted unanimously.
The commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the pendulum watch of the constitutional assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made it possible to apply more strictly.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of the Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this as a propaganda blow, reply to "sacrifice".
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they consider Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt's specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "the people who are asked for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy at all.
You can see here the first signs of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are also nourished by the fact that the next rector of this university should be far less moderate than the current one.
"At present, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been trained in the French system in part," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admitted, however, that "with regard to Article 220, there can be a ambiguity, since the terms used are derived from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, reference is made to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, note "Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to his religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers he grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslims argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Nor will there be a ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights defence organisations have called for.
The latter also share their fears about the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
