In Israel Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort, and unspoiled nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
Bend in front of the holy places
Visit the river Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It means that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the conversion of water into wine at a wedding celebration, the walking on the water, the breastfeeding of the sea tower and the fishing.
Here, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries, however, are found in Jerusalem.
Believers here take the path of suffering or the path of the cross of Jesus Christ (on Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where there are the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, symbolizing the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most holy place of the Jews - the complaint wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, there people of different faiths leave papers with desires that are then fulfilled.
Make a journey up to the level
The ruins of the Massada fortress are the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins of their own strength.
All others bring an air cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were supposedly living on the summit.
Visit Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
On only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among these is once the Israel Museum, not far from the Knesset (parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea found in caves in the Judean desert are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works by the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is on display.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers at that time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops there.
Admission is free and donations are refused in principle.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters of history.
The most touching department is the memorial to the children, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died came.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three main recreation areas of Israel lie on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, in the Red Sea, the water temperature is not below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C even in the winter months.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus even wears non-swimmer easily on the surface.
The landscape landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt soles) and healing sludge, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and the calming of stressed nerves.
The Secrets of Ancientity Touch
These secrets surround the old town of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city was the famous seaway, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow alleyways named after zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be the legend after all who touch the walls in the alley with their star sign.
In Jaffa you can find newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Today evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Favourites for tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your bad English skills: about 30% of the Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is rather taken in no Euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only underground line of the country with six stations connecting the lower city to the upper city.
In fact, it's an underground cable car.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the transport, which is enough to change for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, excluding pigmeat, marine products, fish without sheds and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with hammock and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls made of pure beans and peas (palafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israeli cities there are no stranding dogs.
For this, there are many well-nourished cats who plow comfortably and unlit through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like lively places and don't say no to treats.
A car rental cost between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs an additional $15 a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
On average, admission tickets for museums cost 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Country, which corresponds to an increase of 51% compared to the period of comparison in 2010, prior to the abolition of the visa obligation on 9 February 2011.
"The great and powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While MEPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates
Each year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant to take a test to certify knowledge of the Russian language.
To date, this scheme applies only to migrants who wish to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, in the future, the tests will become compulsory for all guest workers, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
Not only language tests, but also tests on Russian history and the foundations of legislation must be carried out.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the receipt and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas prior to the break-up of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The whole of the examination bodies will be under the aegide of the Puschkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of People's Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to launch the tests was supported by the representatives of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
However, before the entry into force of the law in the press, civil rights activists asked the following question several times: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the rule of having to show language skills, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, spokespersons from the Migration Authority, it is about reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says the head of the representative office of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelev.
However, their rights must be protected from departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical evaluation are facing problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who put him in a dark, narrow barracks under the pretext of help, where he will endure with dozens of his equal months without food and documents and created 12 to 14 hours a day.
We reach many complaints from our migrants.
"In the home country, you will be promised the One, and on arrival you will be deceived, their passports will be taken off and will not receive the promised wage," confirms the head of the main labour migration administration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't beg your pardon, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they cannot only control the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbekistan and Tajiks can afford only reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school items.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to reside illegally in Russia.
"Welcome welcome" or "forbidden entry for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for a thousand and a half.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly faked and we are not registered, and that results in cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tajik Umed Huschkadamov to journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the cost of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be faked.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save themselves the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The most important direct task is to protect the system from corruption so that certificates cannot be bought easily, both officials and civil rights activists agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
