According to the authors in Moscow, any weapon for little money can be found.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the battles in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel come illegal weapons that are stolen from criminals' guardians.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both the police's arms chambers and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
In many military camps, explosions often occurred.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not withstand international competition and are therefore squandering weapons under the hand of the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is the smuggling.
Especially many guns and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is an own, sometimes craft production, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military member.
