"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I do not think this is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative example of practice, he leads the attitude of Prime Minister Petr Nečas to the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls - is the system now prohibited or permitted?
"A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the chairman of the government cannot simply come, and the control office, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, can hinder its activity," Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Chamber of Deputies' Control Committee, you discussed a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries relating to public procurement were compared.
What was that specifically about?
This is a parallel examination that we started about two years ago.
In simple terms, it is a matter of European legislation defining how public procurement can be handled, on which the national legislation is based, and finally there is the actual practical application.
We compared all of this with each other, and although the examination has not yet been completed, we were able to see very interesting differences. In general, the laws are perhaps even more "harder and more perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to set new and more precise rules over and over again. One must also consider the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What is the result of this project for you?
This kind of joint control could help us to stop constantly trying to perfect the laws and reduce and erode thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Economic efficiency means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the reduction of thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we also achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even so that in this way we burden the system only with excessive "paperwork" and those looking for gaps in the system have much easier to use the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
They talk about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech procurement law.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an authority similar to our NKÜ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ of the Bundeskonsultshof, which is similar to that of us and also has a college, which is just a little different, but in principle, both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also comparable to some extent, but Germany is a state, i.e. there are these accounting courts in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH can only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds managed by the districts and municipalities are subject to the control of the national accounting authorities.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
