Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of this Space Authority at a Council of Ministers meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency ESA. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (according to the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started working closely with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland to space, of course, began much earlier.
Before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were already engaged in space travel, and they did not always come to understand it.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Entry to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, for "Entry to Cosmomics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's internationally recognized contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earth's side of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket engine was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project unfortunately remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or brake the drain.
The information comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered shots.
The research was carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslav Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents that have been passed that research had reached the stage of practical tests.
The research was, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket appeared in the specialist press of Rohoziński, and the following year, the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all the projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work its work was finished from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space were published after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polkie Towarzystwo Astronautczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society was made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space society.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be noted that the exploration of space would have future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Society PTA sought to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member as early as autumn 1956.
The following year the first PTA President, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was appointed Deputy President of the International Federation of Space.
In 1959, he was appointed to the post of President of the United States.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a major role in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first one was launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 the Błędów desert began flight tests with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach altitudes of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of altitude winds.
However, further development was discontinued in 1962.
The first RM rocket was replaced by the Meteor 1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport room with a capacity of 0.4 litres, meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude was 37 km for all three types.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
Also worth mentioning is Poland's accession to the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960, followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
