In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamic students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they demanded the delivery of the crashed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had kept the cartridge over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have greatly damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent Fiasco in the violent attempt to release hostages made everything worse.
The prisoners were finally released after 444 days after negotiations by the Algerian government had been arranged.
The fate of the hostages caused at home a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranic moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the message, six embassies succeeded in fleeing.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran; an extravagant story helped them to hide their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film stand, allegedly visiting film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time, based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
Thus the mood levels alternate in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly uppermost.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the official hallways, on the phone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable restart to his career.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Krimi No Children's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film that doesn't play in the director's home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck proves this feeling, however, in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the opening sequence of the first storm of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team have a similar effect in fictitious scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not really offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
With the few, however, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping with reality - which does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the imminent crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or also the pursuit on the runway, appear somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its all too wide scatter, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their figures deserve more space, so they are far from alone in the film.
Affeck’s film thus loses a bit of tensile strength. It is a film that can be followed with a certain interest and the design and the retro-style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th years.
But enthusiasm is hard to awaken.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive in a certain way today and as evidence of how overlaid the ideas of all-powerful and all-knowing intelligence services are, he is sufficient.
