Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role"
Germany has abstained in the vote on the reception of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin is thus balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had first signaled that it would vote against the request for observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin included itself.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about setting up a flight ban zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is turning its foreign policy away from a policy managed by the US, so to speak, towards a German foreign policy.
In addition, it is difficult to see that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching on their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or Great Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean in concrete terms from the German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions with national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that the German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. of exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to face the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
This certainly plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to give too much weight to this either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from the vote in important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That's why I don't think this was such a dramatic break, as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for it.
Because it does signal that as an international player it must be taken seriously and its interests must be considered.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly declared itself to be a veto.
Are there differences between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed because of American domestic policy.
I believe that the government under Obama is secretly well aware of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as big as they always appear.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so excited about Netanyahu's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the USA on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and must instead drive things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, even because of the relationship with Israel.
That has always been a sensitive issue.
But I think the Germans are clear that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself in the role as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, there will be a wide range of anti-German feelings free every time Germany assumes a greater role.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
That's actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be receptive to different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now, the US's influence in European politics is constantly decreasing, but the EU is filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they do not like it, it is unpleasant to them and makes it much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly research the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
