Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
The bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and trippers (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papilomavirs, herpes genitalis or hepatitis.
Filuses and scratches belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and trippers occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of the syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonades, candidosis (pilz), tripper and human papilomavirs are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is relatively low - nevertheless: about 20 percent of HIV new infections are due to this group.
Among adolescents, Chlamydia infections occur much more frequently than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
Human papilomavirs are also common in young people in these countries.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has declined since 2007.
There were around 2,700 cases in 2011.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate sexual illness?
The infectious diseases may cause ulcers in the genital area, urination, outflow, lower abdominal pain, blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection but do not provide a 100% protection.
For in some cases pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubricating infections and close contact with the body.
Therefore, experts especially recommend regular investigations in frequently changing sex partners.
Earlyly diagnosed, most STIs can be cured and late consequences avoided.
