After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of wanting to "do a satisfactory job but not be able to do it".
Therefore, boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not employed, but wants to be.
In contrast, in apathy there is no urge to do something.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is in "a disturbance of the attention process, paired with bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly".
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two states may be related, bored persons see the problem in their surroundings or in the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we believe that we are boring, even if we have only difficulty concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - to German for example: "The inactive mind: The definition of boredom under the aspect of attention", which appeared in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed out an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low volume, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard hardly audible television said they felt more boredom than the two other groups - they had problems concentrating, could find no reason for them and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When one tries to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if one carries on one-tone activity - "just like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help to avoid feeling bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that claws and crickets, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically attentive.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hammer around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
All of us get bored at some point - my late flight, a roaring speaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
In order to measure these differences, in the 1980s, researchers developed a "scale of boredom vulnerability".
On the scale, statements like "Many things I have to do repeat and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
With the help of such scales, researchers have found that young people get more bored than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of Westflorida - in particular as regards the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are quite a strained bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of adults were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored if they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents reported feeling bored.
Today, 21 years later, Professor Larson says, he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "youth will be particularly bored", mainly because children and teenagers have no big influence on their everyday life.
So back to my question of origin: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, people take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to relieve them - that's what studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been exploring the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do right now.
If you are bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you will be happy.
However, while television can provide for happiness in the short term, it is now disappearing in the long term.
So if you are enough for your bored child to have an iPad, you can get rid of the boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, "self-control is transferred from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to talk but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we see them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant scope of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be boring more often, but boredom is the painful, unrelenting desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for a way to shut down and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly being overstimulated, it is difficult to get involved once the noise is silent."
