For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by bringing sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano to the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it must climb down to the ground of its crater every day, where the sulphurous gas flowing from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloppy paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle speed, keeping the balance and taking careful steps so that they do not slip out and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened by a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen's miners earn 5 Eurocents for every kilo of sulphur they reduce.
