The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 has been exploiting the occurrences in the volcano and (no better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matchwoods, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"As we normally carry 70 kg, we receive about 46,000 rupees for each path (3.8 euros)", explains Anto, who normally makes three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours to complete it, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (€ 11.5) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such a sheer inhuman effort, however, is the triple of what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees are paid at the coffee harvest (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier who previously worked as a mare on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not as hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason that is as important as the sulphur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali where they are Hindus, and I have brought them to Java to convert them to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of toxic gases.
