Whoever does not take this issue easily is the government of Singapore.
Each year, she spends 1,300 US dollars on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax advantages.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, which is also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was over 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singapore people have children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy of the National Population Authority, says that this is due to "better training" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has enabled people to have much more options and priorities than to marry and form a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of single people and to the delay in marriage and birth, the result of which is the reduction of the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration in order to combat the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where Xenophobia, which is hardly disguised, blooms against many new immigrants, especially against the Chinese who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the government party in Singapore achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and charges for foreign workers.
Expected consequences
While the falling birth rate is the known impact on the economic growth of a nation with tax revenues, health costs and immigration policy, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to achieve that not so many small apartments are built.
It has already had an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" and may be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the life style of the individual, and that they deter construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, Director General of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger housing units.
This results in them being much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give the developers clearer orientations, which were previously introduced to obstacles if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, the talks with the Singaporeese who work in the financial quarter show that they will not have a great impact.
"People are heavily stressed, the apartments and also the education are expensive, which is why it is pushed out by many," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time," says another, about twenty-year-old man.
Men and women point out their career, the stress and the cost of property and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That is why the Singaporeese have the last word when it comes to having children - the government can do so much more.
The offline private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "the area of private life where one is entitled to protection against any kind of interference".
What's private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he exposes if he makes known on the Internet situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are often on the network.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very own" on a personal level and "to the password and user" when they applied it to the social networks.
"My deepest secrets would not be announced in a post," says the 10-year-old Jorge trying to explain the meaning of "private" in websites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or images of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a picture that's not mine, or someone who's making the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, of nude, of crime, or to write insulting or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I logged in to Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I just upload them up," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can quickly talk to relatives in the distance or with friends" he states.
He asked that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone told him a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not to know 20 of the people he has added to his friends list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one made any indications or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone pushes me or asks them for me, I'll just remove him from my user account" he admits.
José joined Ask after reading a recommendation in Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was extorted in a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never learned who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the user account.
"He just made it private."
After that, he explains a number of steps to safely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I'd do that if he was unappreciative to me or I wanted to wipe him out.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, a teacher for English with a university degree in education and learning, says that to guide children and young people, it must be understood that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for searching for information; but with the appearance of these pages, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, owner of a master's title in pedagogy at the University of Yale and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants" formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are they, the children and young people who have grown up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants to teach them, where we still learn," he says.
He explains that it is a complex issue, "because we require them to have a defined criterion on what may be disseminated, published or said, and this at an age where maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be selective when it is most important for them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is to ask them questions that make them think.
"To tell you not to do it, doesn't work," he says.
Then Porras mentions some possibilities: There are things you would not tell a stranger. Then why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like to publish a photo of you, like the one you published from a friend?
Do you know what the others are publishing about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission before you labeled photos of celebrations?
And another question: Do everyone need to know what you are doing at any moment?
Another point is to give them understanding that they have to act online as they do offline.
They're the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet deals with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teachers and educational advisers, commented that it is essential that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
If they understand all sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, the age, or what you may share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children need to be reminded of the lesson "Don't talk to strangers".
Conclusion of the UNASUR Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th meeting of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was theoretically to be signed by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI. Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State or Government of the Unasur. Sources at the State and Presidential Chancellery at the beginning announced that they would hand it over after the clause, but afterwards stated that it would be published at some time on the website of the Peruvian government.
In the case of questions on the text, they indicated that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among journalists was received by press speakers from some of the UNASUR’s governments present at the meeting, but not by Peruvian press spokesperson.
The only document that was disseminated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused displeasure among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more information.
After that, the Presidential Office of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "declaration" of the summit, but it was the declaration of Humala and not the official document for the conclusion of the summit.
Last October Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was not published, despite a strong call from the press.
On the official website of the ASPA you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but they greatly restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague which resolved a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which began on Monday in The Hague, in the trial that Lima initiated against Santiago, to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and implement the ruling on the differences we are currently making to this international court," said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will continue to be a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits itself to international courts," added Piñera and greeted Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The two Presidents confirmed that they would submit to the IGH, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it a serious mistake, had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement, in which they agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court of Justice.
The Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner were present at the summit.
Paraguay, who has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The guest President Ollanta Humala opened the talks on the morning and ended the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state read the final document stating that 16 decisions were taken and 31 lines of action between the South American countries were set for a total investment of $17 billion.
On the decisions taken, he said that the Unasur countries will "take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be promoted to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and against organised cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not take triumphant steps, but should serve to expand our production performance and to show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects to improve spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas...and thus to unite our countries and develop new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read-out statement.
These projects include five Peruvians lying on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although they did not provide any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its reintegration into the Union of South American nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, before beginning his participation in the regional meeting, said that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart to Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to deal respectfully with the maritime conflict following a judgment of the IGH challenged by Bogotá.
"Maybe I'll meet President Daniel Ortega on the morning of Saturday," said Santos.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and respectfully as possible," added Santos.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they intend to be present at the office of the new President of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Ministers of Defence of the Block met in advance to adopt the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru has the Presidency at the time of the regional block.
