He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it; and this with such a commitment that he was celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was difficult to imagine at the beginning of the 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye, "because it led to a dead end."
At that time, AIDS was synonym for death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and in whom the virus has already caused damage and exhausted their immune system, and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who receives treatment in good time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HCG HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
The specialist for infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008 scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the immune system of individuals at the beginning of treatment, and that those who are not drug dependent have greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above statements mean that those who receive HIV-positive diagnosis at the age of 25 can in this sense be "problemless 75 years old as long as they are under control", said this expert.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be recalled that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now an average of 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNUSIDA's annual report), it is still true that 60 percent of the patients listed in the national database have died since AIDS appeared.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year, there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral medicines since 2005.
So why do people still die from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so it is in our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years we have had no problems with the care of the medications. The problem is that the people come in a far advanced state because they do not know their condition of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have a accompanying infection. To be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnosis is required, which is why all persons who need it must be offered massive detection tests."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estate de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Avoidance in Jalisco) and also the patients like Fabrizio who had his test carried out at a private laboratory, and this for the only reason that it had made a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancer-like tumor) which is one of the usual complications.
