Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Hector "Hetin" Reyes, the world boomer of the basketball, was associated with basket sports for more than 60 years and traveled the whole world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a great spiritual collection of the history of the basketball of the country as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a player of lower classes, players of the first national league, authorised and head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Association.
"My life has been a lot of hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was President of the BSN, Chief Executive Officer of the National Team and President of the Association in the 1990s," Reyes recalled on a visit from Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes doesn't exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time at the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-business manager or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most, because I was allowed to be part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967 as Managing Director, Co-Chairman or Trainer.
There were many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I voted with a 1981 championship, the year of Jerome Mincy's debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good administrator," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said, "I have a very strong and 2 m big player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended the free-throwing specialist Raymond Gausse, who became a citizen and was one of our best pitchers.
I remember when he said that if Mincy had made a championship for Bayamon possible, Gausse would take care of another one.
The championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse was awarded to him, but already out of a distance, because he was already in the top position of the association in 1988.
At that time he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember the first time we won against the USA at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Championship, where we finished fourth, which should have been bronze, if not this Canadian referee had been, who had us repeat the last move for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as is the one who won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
My favorite, however, is the team at the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered a fight to the US team, as they did when they won us at the Bronze World Cup.
Not only were Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and Piculín (Ortiz) present, but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 because of knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which gave us great pleasure was that of the 1995 pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner as a substitute for the locked players because of the events at the Pan-American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against any prognosis.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was undoubtedly Piculín Ortiz.
His figures at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated on this level as Piculín.
And this without taking his career into account in the different leagues in which he played.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
That is a difficult question.
We had a number of good trainers like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best you've achieved in the association?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN at the beginning of the 1990s up to 17 teams in one season.
What else are you doing?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalization of the lower categories.
That the guys in Ponce, for example, play only in their territory and only meet teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today the children make unnecessary trips and games.
At least I see the result of the required training and training courses for trainers, table officials and arbitrators.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like listening to music, watching videos of my time music in YouTube, enjoying my grandchildren and occasionally going to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always at my side.
Larry Hagman is dead
Larry Hagman was born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas) and became famous worldwide for his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". in the television series "Dallas", where he played a unscrupulous, insidious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who came back this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died on Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved birthplace of Dallas, where he played the iconic role he liked most," said the family.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebrations of the harvest Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was at Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, her journalist Jeffrey Lane said.
He made everyone happy who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the full", explained Gray in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted to drinking a lot over the years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was detected in his liver, and he was transplanted.
In the years before "Dallas" Hagman became known on television as a nice guy from 1965 to 1970 with the Sitcom "Adorable Jeannie" of the television station NBC.
There he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is put on his head when he meets an attractive "Jinn" (played by Barbara Eden), who will live with him at home.
He also performed two comedies, which were broadcast only for a short time, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his cinema works were well-rated roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the enchanting abominable J.R. who made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of the CBS television series on the Ewing clan and other figures in its surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan "Who shot at J.R.?", which was expected to create expectation of an episode full of emotions where the figure of Hagmann was almost killed, led to an international speculation, and millions of dollars were bet in bets.
This made the series a record of spectators at that time.
When the answer became known in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million spectators who turned "Dallas" into the second most widely seen entertainment program since the end of "Mash" 1983, which had 50 million spectators.
It was Kristin who shot the brother-in-law of J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby).
